article.headline: Liberty come out on top in matchup of rivals
article.linkText: Liberty stave off Comets to rise in East
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Liberty proved they can play with the best of the West. After knocking off the defending champion Los Angeles Sparks 10 days ago, the Liberty held off the Houston Comets 62-56 on Sunday. Vickie Johnson and Tamika Whitmore combined for four free throws in the final 33 seconds as the Liberty (15-10) moved within a half-game of Eastern Conference-leading Washington with seven games left in the season. Whitmore made the final two free throws and finished with 15 points and a season-high nine rebounds for the Liberty. Johnson had 14 points on 5-for-8 shooting, and Tari Phillips added 13 points and nine rebounds. "I'd have to say two of the best rivalries in the WNBA are New York vs. LA and New York vs. Houston,'' Johnson said. "Every single time the teams step on the court, it's a great game, the highest level of basketball.'' Sheryl Swoopes scored 26 points and Tina Thompson had 16 for the Comets (19-7), who dropped two games behind Western Conference leader Los Angeles. Houston, which plays five of its final six games at home, had a chance to clinch a playoff berth with a win. After Thompson's 3-pointer made it 58-56, Johnson and Whitmore combined at the charity stripe for the final margin. Swoopes returned to Madison Square Garden for the first time in two years after sitting out last season with a knee injury. "It's a good rivalry,'' Swoopes said. "Not to be a part of that last year is definitely something I missed. The game was definitely one we wanted to win. They just wanted it more.'' New York has won three straight against Houston and leads the regular-season series 8-5. But the Comets beat the Liberty when it mattered, clinching the 1997, 1999 and 2000 WNBA titles. New York nearly gave it away, turning the ball over three times in the final three minutes. Holding a seven-point lead, the Liberty failed to convert on consecutive possessions after bad passes by Teresa Weatherspoon. Swoopes capitalized with a driving layup to cut the lead to 56-51 with 1:30 left. New York had a shot-clock violation with 45 seconds left and Swoopes' layup closed it to 56-53. Robinson, who finished with 10 points, made two free throws after Swoopes fouled her for a 58-53 lead with 35 seconds left. Thompson quickly sank a 3-pointer to get within two, but Houston could get no closer. Swoopes was called for traveling in the Comets' final possession, and Johnson dribbled out the final seconds to a standing ovation from the Madison Square Garden crowd of 17,368. "Today was a huge win for us,'' Johnson said. "It helps us keep the momentum going, keeps us focused on improving our position in the playoffs. At this point in the season, this is what it's all about.'' Tied at halftime, New York opened a 43-34 lead with 11 minutes left behind five points by Johnson. Whitmore capped the 16-7 run with a banker in the lane over 6-foot-5 Michelle Snow. Phillips made a turnaround baseline jumper over two defenders for a 10-point lead before Swoopes sank an NBA 3-pointer to trail 48-41 with 7:50 left. The Comets scored four quick points after Johnson was called for a flagrant foul on Swoopes after a steal and breakaway. Swoopes converted the two free throws and Thompson made a putback to cut the lead to 51-47. "I thought we did a good job of coming back,'' Houston coach Van Chancellor said. "It's a hard thing to spot a good team leads in both halves.''

Game notes
The Liberty won their fifth straight at Madison Square Garden. ... New York beat the Sparks 72-59 on July 18. ... Houston had won 14 of its last 17 coming in. ... The Comets were 2-for-13 from 3-point range. ... Rebecca Lobo, an original member of the Liberty who was traded to Houston during the preseason, entered the game to cheers with 11 minutes left and was scoreless in two minutes in her first regular-season return to the Garden.
